"Dorman L.I.","Cosmic ray variations and space weather",2010,"Physics-Uspekhi","53","5",,"496","503",,,10.3367/UFNe.0180.201005g.0519,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77958615234&partnerID=40&md5=f933fe58ff164d782e1912bac4d6b5ea","Israel Cosmic Ray and Space Weather Center with the Emilio Ségre Observatory, Tel Aviv University, Technion, Israel Space Agency, Israel; Pushkov Institute of Terrestrial Magnetism, Ionosphere, and Radio Wave Propagation (IZMIRAN), Russian Academy of Sciences, Troitsk, Moscow Region, Russian Federation","Dorman, L.I., Israel Cosmic Ray and Space Weather Center with the Emilio Ségre Observatory, Tel Aviv University, Technion, Israel Space Agency, Israel, Pushkov Institute of Terrestrial Magnetism, Ionosphere, and Radio Wave Propagation (IZMIRAN), Russian Academy of Sciences, Troitsk, Moscow Region, Russian Federation","The relationship of cosmic ray variation (CR) with space weather issue investigated at the Research Institute of Terrestrial Magnetism (IZMIR) is discussed. CR of galactic and solar origin influence Earth's atmosphere through nuclear reactions of primary and secondary CR with air and aerosol matter accompanied by the formation of many unstable and stable cosmogenic nuclides. The generation of secondary relativistic electrons by CR in the atmosphere and extensive atmospheric showers (EAS) has a significant role in atmospheric electric field phenomena such as thunderstorms, discharges, and Earth's electric charge balance. Changes in Earth's magnetosphere are caused by long-term variations of the main geomagnetic field and by electric currents in the magnetosphere and ionosphere. International CR Variation Service allows continuous determination of the change in time of the angle-energy CR distribution outside Earth's magnetosphere by one-hour CR data from the world-wide network of neutron monitors and telescopes.",,"Cosmic rays; Electric discharges; Electric fields; Geomagnetism; Ionosphere; Magnetosphere; Nuclear energy; Nuclear reactors; Thunderstorms; Atmospheric electric field; Cosmogenic nuclides; Earth's magnetosphere; Extensive atmospheric showers; Geomagnetic fields; Long-term variations; Neutron monitors; Nuclear reactions; Relativistic electron; Research institutes; Space weather; Terrestrial magnetism; World-wide networks; Earth atmosphere",,,,,,"Dorman, L.I., (1957) Cosmic Ray Variations, , Variatsii Kosmicheskikh Luchei, Moscow: Gostekhteorizdat, Translated into English Washington, DC: US Department of Defence, Ohio Air-Force Base, 1957; Dorman, L.I., (2004) Cosmic Rays in the Earth's Atmosphere and Underground, , Dordrecht: Kluwer Acad. Publ; Dorman, L.I., (2006) Cosmic Ray Interactions, Propagation, and Acceleration in Space Plasmas, , Dordrecht: Springer; Dorman, L.I., (2009) Cosmic Rays in Magnetospheres of the Earth and Other Planets, , Dordrecht: Springer; Dorman, L.I., Yanke, V.G., (1981) Proc. of the 17th Intern. Cosmic Ray Conf., 4, p. 326. , Paris, France; Dorman, L.I., Yanke, V.G., Korotkov, V.K., (1981) Proc. 17th of the Intern. Cosmic Ray Conf., 4, p. 330. , V K, in, Paris, France; Clem, J.M., Dorman, L.I., (2000) Space Sci. Rev., 93, p. 335; Aleksanyan, T.M., Dorman, L.I., Yanke, V.G., Korotkov, V.K., (1985) Proc. of the 19th Intern. Cosmic Ray Conf., 5, p. 300. , La Jolla, USA; Moraal, H., (1989) J. Geophys. Res., 94 (A2), p. 1459; Dorman, L.I., (2000) J. Geophys. Res., 105 (A9), p. 21047; Dorman, L.I., (1969) Proc. of the 11th Intern. Cosmic Ray Conf., p. 381. , Budapest, Invited Papers and Rapporteur Talks; Dorman, L.I., Gushchina, R.T., Smart, D.F., Shea, M.A., (1972) Effective Cut-Off Rigidities of Cosmic Rays, , Moscow: Nauka; Dorman, L.I., (1974) Cosmic Rays: Variations and Space Explorations, , Amsterdam: North-Holland; Dorman, L.I., (1972) Meteorological Effects of Cosmic Rays, , Moscow: Nauka; Dorman, L.I., (2003) J. Geophys. Res., 108 (A5), p. 1181; Dorman, L.I., (1977) Proc. of the 15th Intern. Cosmic Ray Conf., 4, p. 374. , Plovdi